## 2. Sprague-Grundy for impartial games

**Opening: generalizing Nim**

Not all games are nim. Consider *Dawson's Kayles*: a row of pins; you knock down one pin or two adjacent pins. Or *Subtraction games*: from a pile of N, you may subtract any element of a fixed set S. Sprague and Grundy proved: every impartial game position has a Grundy number, computed as mex of the Grundy numbers of its successors. Positions with Grundy number 0 are losing (previous player wins); nonzero are winning.

**Subtraction game S={1,3,4}:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; compute Grundy numbers -->
```scheme
(define S (list 1 3 4))

(define (grundy-subtraction n allowed)
  (if (<= n 0)
      0
      (let ((succs (filter (lambda (m) (>= m 0))
                           (map (lambda (s) (- n s)) allowed))))
        (game/mex (map (lambda (m) (grundy-subtraction m allowed)) succs)))))

(map (lambda (n) (grundy-subtraction n S)) (comb/range 0 16))
```
[VISUAL: sequence of Grundy numbers for n=0..15 in S={1,3,4} game, showing eventual period.]

**Detecting the period for subtraction games:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; show periodicity emerges -->
```scheme
(define long-seq (map (lambda (n) (grundy-subtraction n S)) (comb/range 0 40)))
long-seq
```
[VISUAL: list showing Grundy numbers repeat after some initial segment (Sprague-Grundy theorem guarantees eventual periodicity).]

**Two-pile subtraction game:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; combine two piles via nim-sum -->
```scheme
(define pile1 7)
(define pile2 5)
(define g1 (grundy-subtraction pile1 S))
(define g2 (grundy-subtraction pile2 S))
(define combined-g (game/nim-sum (list g1 g2)))

(list 'pile1 pile1 'g1 g1 'pile2 pile2 'g2 g2 'combined combined-g
      'outcome (if (= combined-g 0) 'losing 'winning))
```
[VISUAL: text showing Grundy number for each pile, their nim-sum, and outcome.]

**Green Hackenbush on a path (another impartial game):**

A path of *n* edges; players alternate removing an edge (and everything above it). This is isomorphic to nim pile of size *n* (Grundy number = *n*), but we can verify via mex:

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; compute Grundy for Hackenbush path -->
```scheme
(define (grundy-hackenbush-path n)
  (if (<= n 0)
      0
      (game/mex (map grundy-hackenbush-path (comb/range 0 n)))))

(map grundy-hackenbush-path (comb/range 0 8))
```
[VISUAL: `(0 1 2 3 4 5 6 7)` — confirms isomorphism to nim.]

**Star *n in combinatorial game theory:**

Conway's *star* notation: *0 is the zero game, *1 is the game where first player wins in one move. `game/star-n` returns a representation of the star-*n game:

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; show star values -->
```scheme
(map game/star-n (comb/range 0 5))
```
[VISUAL: list of star game representations, e.g. `((*0) (*1) (*2) (*3) (*4))`.]

**Grundy number from star:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; extract Grundy number from star -->
```scheme
(map (lambda (n)
       (let ((star (game/star-n n)))
         (list 'star-n n 'grundy (game/grundy star))))
     (comb/range 0 5))
```
[VISUAL: `((star-n 0 grundy 0) (star-n 1 grundy 1) ...)` — Grundy(*n) = n.]

**Adding stars:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; add *2 + *3 -->
```scheme
(define star2 (game/star-n 2))
(define star3 (game/star-n 3))
(define sum23 (game/nim-sum (list (game/grundy star2) (game/grundy star3))))

(list 'star2 (game/grundy star2) 'star3 (game/grundy star3) 'sum sum23)
```
[VISUAL: `(star2 2 star3 3 sum 1)` — 2⊕3=1, so *2+*3 = *1.]

**Building a small game tree with Grundy labels:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; recursive tree structure -->
```scheme
(define (game-tree-grundy n allowed depth)
  (if (or (<= n 0) (<= depth 0))
      (list 'position n 'grundy 0 'terminal #t)
      (let* ((succs (filter (lambda (m) (>= m 0))
                            (map (lambda (s) (- n s)) allowed)))
             (succ-trees (map (lambda (m) (game-tree-grundy m allowed (- depth 1))) succs))
             (succ-grundys (map (lambda (t) (cadr (assoc 'grundy t))) succ-trees))
             (g (game/mex succ-grundys)))
        (list 'position n 'grundy g 'successors succ-trees))))

(game-tree-grundy 5 (list 1 2) 3)
```
[VISUAL: nested tree showing position 5, its Grundy number, and recursive successor trees down to depth 3.]

**Checking a position is losing by Grundy number:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; test position -->
```scheme
(define pos 8)
(define allowed (list 1 3 4))
(define g (grundy-subtraction pos allowed))

(if (= g 0)
    (list 'position pos 'is 'losing)
    (list 'position pos 'is 'winning 'grundy g))
```
[VISUAL: text showing whether position 8 in S={1,3,4} is winning or losing.]

**Finding the winning move via Grundy:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; search for move leaving Grundy 0 -->
```scheme
(define (find-winning-move-grundy n allowed)
  (let ((g (grundy-subtraction n allowed)))
    (if (= g 0)
        '(losing-position)
        (let loop ((moves allowed))
          (if (null? moves)
              '(no-move-found)
              (let* ((move (car moves))
                     (after (- n move)))
                (if (and (>= after 0) (= (grundy-subtraction after allowed) 0))
                    (list 'subtract move 'leaving after)
                    (loop (cdr moves)))))))))

(find-winning-move-grundy 10 (list 1 3 4))
```
[VISUAL: `(subtract 1 leaving 9)` or similar — the move that zeroes the Grundy number.]

