## 4. Minimax and game trees

**Opening: solving finite games**

When a game has finite depth—tic-tac-toe, small chess endgames, Connect Four on a small board—we can compute the *value* of every position by backward induction. The *minimax* algorithm: at a MAX node (your turn), pick the move with maximum value; at a MIN node (opponent's turn), pick minimum. If both play optimally, the value of the root is the game's outcome. We represent values as numbers (positive = you win, negative = you lose, 0 = draw) or as categoricals ('win, 'lose, 'draw).

**Tic-tac-toe—terminal position value:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; evaluate a finished board -->
```scheme
(define board-x-wins '((x x x)
                       (o o -)
                       (- - -)))

(game/ttt-value board-x-wins)
```
[VISUAL: `'win-x` or numeric 1 — X has won.]

**Tic-tac-toe—draw position:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; full board, no winner -->
```scheme
(define board-draw '((x o x)
                     (o x o)
                     (o x o)))

(game/ttt-value board-draw)
```
[VISUAL: `'draw` or 0 — board full, no winner.]

**Finding the best move:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; ask for optimal move for X -->
```scheme
(define board-in-progress '((x o x)
                            (o - -)
                            (- - -)))

(game/ttt-best-move board-in-progress 'x)
```
[VISUAL: `(1 1)` or similar — the row/col of the best move for X (center, blocks O and threatens win).]

**Minimax value of an opening position:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; empty board or near-empty -->
```scheme
(define empty-board '((- - -)
                      (- - -)
                      (- - -)))

(game/ttt-value empty-board)
```
[VISUAL: `'draw` or 0 — with optimal play, tic-tac-toe is a draw from empty board.]

**Minimax on a trivial game tree (manual):**

We build a simple 2-ply tree and compute minimax by hand:

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; manual minimax on explicit tree -->
```scheme
(define (minimax-tree node is-max)
  (if (assoc 'value node)
      (cadr (assoc 'value node))
      (let* ((children (cadr (assoc 'children node)))
             (child-vals (map (lambda (c) (minimax-tree c (not is-max))) children)))
        (if is-max
            (apply max child-vals)
            (apply min child-vals)))))

(define tree '(node (children ((node (value 3))
                               (node (value 5))
                               (node (value 2))))))

(minimax-tree tree #t)
```
[VISUAL: `5` — MAX picks the maximum of {3,5,2}.]

**Minimax with alpha-beta bounds (conceptual):**

Alpha-beta pruning skips branches that can't affect the result. We don't have a wired alpha-beta verb, so we show the idea in prose: track alpha (best MAX can guarantee) and beta (best MIN can guarantee); prune when alpha ≥ beta.

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; annotated tree with pruning notes -->
```scheme
(define tree-with-prune
  '(node (children ((node (value 3))
                   (node (children ((node (value 2))
                                    (node (value 8))))) ; MIN will pick 2, so 8 not evaluated if we had pruning
                   (node (value 5))))))

; Manual minimax (no pruning wired):
(minimax-tree tree-with-prune #t)
```
[VISUAL: `5` — result same as full minimax, but note that in alpha-beta we'd skip evaluating 8 once we see 2.]

**Small Nim as a minimax tree:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; build tree for nim pile of 3, max-take 2 -->
```scheme
(define (nim-tree-restricted n max-take depth player)
  (if (or (<= n 0) (<= depth 0))
      (list 'position n 'value (if (= n 0) (if (eq? player 'max) -1 1) 0) 'terminal #t)
      (let* ((moves (filter (lambda (t) (<= t n)) (comb/range 1 (+ max-take 1))))
             (children (map (lambda (t) (nim-tree-restricted (- n t) max-take (- depth 1)
                                                             (if (eq? player 'max) 'min 'max)))
                            moves))
             (child-vals (map (lambda (c) (cadr (assoc 'value c))) children))
             (value (if (eq? player 'max) (apply max child-vals) (apply min child-vals))))
        (list 'position n 'player player 'value value 'children children))))

(nim-tree-restricted 3 2 5 'max)
```
[VISUAL: nested tree showing position 3, its value, and all descendant positions with their minimax values.]

**Reading the optimal move from the tree:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; find child with value = parent value -->
```scheme
(define (optimal-move-from-tree tree)
  (let* ((value (cadr (assoc 'value tree)))
         (children (cadr (assoc 'children tree)))
         (child-vals (map (lambda (c) (cadr (assoc 'value c))) children)))
    (let loop ((cs children) (vs child-vals) (i 0))
      (if (null? cs)
          '(no-move)
          (if (= (car vs) value)
              (list 'move i 'to (cadr (assoc 'position (car cs))))
              (loop (cdr cs) (cdr vs) (+ i 1)))))))

(optimal-move-from-tree (nim-tree-restricted 3 2 5 'max))
```
[VISUAL: `(move 1 to 1)` — take 2, leaving 1 for opponent (who then takes 1 and loses).]

**Temperature of a game (hot vs cold):**

Conway's *temperature* measures how urgent a move is. A cold game (temperature 0) has a definite value; a hot game is worth fighting over. `game/temperature` returns this:

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; temperature of *1 -->
```scheme
(game/temperature (game/star-n 1))
```
[VISUAL: `1.0` or similar — *1 has temperature 1.]

**Temperature of a number game:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; temperature of {2|3} -->
```scheme
(define hot-game (game/surreal (list two) (list (game/surreal (list two) '()))))
(game/temperature hot-game)
```
[VISUAL: nonzero if the game is fuzzy; 0 if it's a number.]

