## 5. Siteswap juggling notation

**Opening: encoding throws as integers**

Jugglers discovered in the 1980s that any periodic juggling pattern can be written as a sequence of integers, where each integer is the \"height\" of a throw (in beats). A 3-ball cascade is `3`; a 4-ball fountain is `4`; a shower is `51`. The *siteswap condition*: a sequence is jugglable if and only if the sum (mod length) is 0 and no two balls land at the same time. More formally: the sequence `(a₀ a₁ ... a_{n-1})` is valid if `{(i + aᵢ) mod n}` for i=0..(n-1) are all distinct.

**Why it matters:** siteswap turns pattern invention into a combinatorial search—find all valid sequences of length 3, or all 4-ball patterns with max throw 5—and lets jugglers share patterns as text.

**Validating a simple siteswap:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; check if `(3 3 3)` is valid -->
```scheme
(juggle/valid? '(3 3 3))
```
[VISUAL: `#t` — the 3-ball cascade is valid (every throw is 3, balls cycle).]

**Counting balls in a pattern:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; how many balls in `(5 3 1)`? -->
```scheme
(juggle/balls '(5 3 1))
```
[VISUAL: `3` — average throw height (5+3+1)/3 = 3, so 3 balls.]

**Invalid pattern—collision:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; `(3 3)` invalid -->
```scheme
(juggle/valid? '(3 3))
```
[VISUAL: `#f` — both throws land at the same beat mod 2 (collision).]

**The shower pattern `(5 1)`:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; validate and count balls -->
```scheme
(list (juggle/valid? '(5 1))
      (juggle/balls '(5 1)))
```
[VISUAL: `(#t 3)` — shower is valid, 3 balls (average 3).]

**The 4-ball fountain `(4)`:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; single-number pattern -->
```scheme
(list (juggle/valid? '(4))
      (juggle/balls '(4)))
```
[VISUAL: `(#t 4)` — synchronous 4 in each hand, 4 balls.]

**Simulating a siteswap—where are the balls?**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; simulate `(5 3 1)` for 6 beats -->
```scheme
(juggle/simulate '(5 3 1) 6)
```
[VISUAL: list of states, each showing which hand holds/throws which ball at each beat.]

**Max throw height in a pattern:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; max throw in `(7 4 1)` -->
```scheme
(juggle/max-throw '(7 4 1))
```
[VISUAL: `7` — highest throw is 7.]

**State representation—current balls in the air:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; show state at beat 0 for `(3 3 3)` -->
```scheme
(juggle/state '(3 3 3) 0)
```
[VISUAL: a-list or list showing which slots are occupied, e.g. `((0 . 1) (1 . 1) (2 . 1))` if all three beats have a ball landing.]

**Generating all 3-ball siteswaps of length 3:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; enumerate valid patterns -->
```scheme
(define (all-siteswaps length balls)
  (filter juggle/valid? (juggle/generate length balls)))

(all-siteswaps 3 3)
```
[VISUAL: list of valid patterns, e.g. `((3 3 3) (5 2 2) (4 4 1) (5 3 1) (4 2 3) ...)` — all valid 3-ball, period-3 patterns.]

**Detecting ground-state (all 3s):**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; is `(3 3 3)` the cascade? -->
```scheme
(equal? '(3 3 3) (make-list 3 3))
```
[VISUAL: `#t` — trivial check, but useful to recognize the default pattern.]

**A harder pattern—`(7 5 3 1)`:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; validate and simulate -->
```scheme
(list 'valid (juggle/valid? '(7 5 3 1))
      'balls (juggle/balls '(7 5 3 1))
      'simulation (juggle/simulate '(7 5 3 1) 8))
```
[VISUAL: valid, 4 balls, state sequence showing throws and catches.]

**Asynchronous vs synchronous patterns:**

Siteswap as described is asynchronous (hands alternate). Synchronous siteswap uses pairs `(a,b)`. We focus on async; note that `(4,4)` is the 4-ball fountain in sync notation, equivalent to `4` in async.

**Excited-state patterns—`(5 5 5)` vs `(3 3 3)`:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; compare two 3-ball patterns -->
```scheme
(list (list 'pattern '(3 3 3) 'balls (juggle/balls '(3 3 3)) 'max (juggle/max-throw '(3 3 3)))
      (list 'pattern '(5 5 5) 'balls (juggle/balls '(5 5 5)) 'max (juggle/max-throw '(5 5 5))))
```
[VISUAL: both are 3-ball patterns, but (5 5 5) has higher throws (excited state).]

**The 4-ball pattern `(5 3)`:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; validate and simulate -->
```scheme
(list (juggle/valid? '(5 3))
      (juggle/balls '(5 3))
      (juggle/simulate '(5 3) 8))
```
[VISUAL: valid, 4 balls (avg 4), state showing 5-throw and 3-throw alternation.]

**Invalid due to non-integer average:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; `(5 2)` invalid -->
```scheme
(list (juggle/valid? '(5 2))
      (juggle/balls '(5 2)))
```
[VISUAL: if valid? returns #f, balls might return non-integer or 'nan — pattern physically impossible.]

**The multiplex throw (conceptual)—not in basic siteswap:**

Siteswap can be extended to multiplex (throw >1 ball from one hand). Standard siteswap assumes one ball per throw; we note the extension but don't have wired multiplex verbs.

**Pattern length vs period:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; period-5 pattern -->
```scheme
(define pat5 '(7 4 4 4 1))
(list 'length (length pat5)
      'valid (juggle/valid? pat5)
      'balls (juggle/balls pat5))
```
[VISUAL: length 5, valid, 4 balls — a 5-beat repeating pattern.]

**Enumerating all valid 4-ball patterns of length 4:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; generate and filter -->
```scheme
(all-siteswaps 4 4)
```
[VISUAL: list of valid 4-ball, period-4 siteswaps, e.g. `((4 4 4 4) (6 4 2 4) (5 5 3 3) ...)` — many patterns.]

**Simulating a long run—`(5 3 1)` for 30 beats:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; long simulation -->
```scheme
(juggle/simulate '(5 3 1) 30)
```
[VISUAL: long list of states, showing the pattern repeats every 3 beats, balls cycling through the air.]

**The \"423\" pattern:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; classic 3-ball trick -->
```scheme
(list (juggle/valid? '(4 2 3))
      (juggle/balls '(4 2 3))
      (juggle/max-throw '(4 2 3)))
```
[VISUAL: valid, 3 balls, max throw 4 — one high throw, one pause, one normal.]

**Siteswap sum rule:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; verify sum(pattern)/length = balls -->
```scheme
(define pat '(5 3 1))
(let ((s (apply + pat))
      (n (length pat)))
  (= (/ s n) (juggle/balls pat)))
```
[VISUAL: `#t` — the siteswap sum rule holds.]

