## 6. Payoff matrices and Nash equilibria (brief)

**Opening: strategic form games**

When games are *not* sequential (both players choose simultaneously), we represent them as *payoff matrices*. Each player picks a strategy (row/column), and the cell shows the outcome for each. Example: Prisoner's Dilemma, Rock-Paper-Scissors. A *Nash equilibrium* is a strategy profile where no player benefits from unilaterally changing their choice. Finding Nash equilibria in 2×2 games is straightforward; larger games or mixed strategies require linear algebra or optimization.

**Prisoner's Dilemma payoff matrix:**

We represent the matrix as nested lists: each row is `(payoff-for-row-player payoff-for-col-player)`.

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; define and print matrix -->
```scheme
(define pd-matrix
  (list (list (list -1 -1) (list -3  0))  ; row 0: Cooperate
        (list (list  0 -3) (list -2 -2)))) ; row 1: Defect

pd-matrix
```
[VISUAL: text showing matrix, e.g. `((((-1 -1) (-3 0)) ((0 -3) (-2 -2))))` — top-left is mutual cooperation, bottom-right mutual defection.]

**Finding dominant strategy:**

In PD, Defect dominates Cooperate for both players.

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; check row-player's dominant strategy -->
```scheme
(define (dominant-strategy-row matrix)
  (let* ((row0 (car matrix))
         (row1 (cadr matrix))
         (r0c0 (car (car row0)))
         (r0c1 (car (cadr row0)))
         (r1c0 (car (car row1)))
         (r1c1 (car (cadr row1))))
    (cond
      ((and (> r1c0 r0c0) (> r1c1 r0c1)) 'defect-dominates)
      ((and (> r0c0 r1c0) (> r0c1 r1c1)) 'cooperate-dominates)
      (else 'no-dominant))))

(dominant-strategy-row pd-matrix)
```
[VISUAL: `'defect-dominates` — row 1 (Defect) gives higher payoff in both columns.]

**Nash equilibrium in PD:**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; equilibrium is (Defect, Defect) -->
```scheme
(define nash-pd (list 1 1))  ; (row, col) indices
(let ((row (list-ref pd-matrix (car nash-pd)))
      (cell (list-ref (list-ref pd-matrix (car nash-pd)) (cadr nash-pd))))
  (list 'strategy nash-pd 'payoffs cell))
```
[VISUAL: `(strategy (1 1) payoffs (-2 -2))` — mutual defection is Nash equilibrium, both get -2.]

**Rock-Paper-Scissors (zero-sum):**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; RPS matrix -->
```scheme
(define rps-matrix
  (list (list (list  0  0) (list -1  1) (list  1 -1))  ; Rock
        (list (list  1 -1) (list  0  0) (list -1  1))  ; Paper
        (list (list -1  1) (list  1 -1) (list  0  0)))) ; Scissors

rps-matrix
```
[VISUAL: 3×3 matrix, e.g. Rock vs Paper gives (-1,1) — row loses, col wins.]

**Mixed strategy equilibrium in RPS:**

No pure Nash; equilibrium is (1/3, 1/3, 1/3) for both players. We state this in prose (computing mixed equilibria requires solving linear systems or linear programming, which is possible with `linalg/solve` but verbose for a 3×3 case). We demonstrate the idea by showing expected payoff is 0:

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; expected value of (1/3,1/3,1/3) vs any opponent strategy -->
```scheme
(define (expected-payoff-rps my-mixed opp-pure-idx)
  (let* ((row (list-ref rps-matrix opp-pure-idx))
         (vals (map (lambda (cell) (car cell)) row)))
    (* (/ 1 3) (apply + vals))))

(map (lambda (i) (expected-payoff-rps '(1/3 1/3 1/3) i)) (list 0 1 2))
```
[VISUAL: `(0 0 0)` — playing (1/3,1/3,1/3) against Rock, Paper, or Scissors all yield expected payoff 0 for row player.]

**Battle of the Sexes (coordination game):**

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; BoS matrix -->
```scheme
(define bos-matrix
  (list (list (list 2 1) (list 0 0))  ; row prefers Opera
        (list (list 0 0) (list 1 2)))) ; row prefers Football

bos-matrix
```
[VISUAL: two pure Nash equilibria: (Opera, Opera) and (Football, Football).]

**Finding pure Nash in a 2×2:**

A cell (r,c) is pure Nash if row player has no incentive to deviate (r is best response to c) and col player has no incentive to deviate (c is best response to r).

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; test both cells -->
```scheme
(define (best-response-row matrix col-choice)
  (let ((r0-payoff (car (list-ref (car matrix) col-choice)))
        (r1-payoff (car (list-ref (cadr matrix) col-choice))))
    (if (> r0-payoff r1-payoff) 0 1)))

(define (best-response-col matrix row-choice)
  (let* ((row (list-ref matrix row-choice))
         (c0-payoff (cadr (car row)))
         (c1-payoff (cadr (cadr row))))
    (if (> c0-payoff c1-payoff) 0 1)))

(define (is-pure-nash? matrix r c)
  (and (= r (best-response-row matrix c))
       (= c (best-response-col matrix r))))

(list (list 'cell '(0 0) 'nash? (is-pure-nash? bos-matrix 0 0))
      (list 'cell '(1 1) 'nash? (is-pure-nash? bos-matrix 1 1))
      (list 'cell '(0 1) 'nash? (is-pure-nash? bos-matrix 0 1))
      (list 'cell '(1 0) 'nash? (is-pure-nash? bos-matrix 1 0)))
```
[VISUAL: `((cell (0 0) nash? #t) (cell (1 1) nash? #t) ...)` — (0,0) and (1,1) are Nash.]

**Pareto efficiency:**

A cell is Pareto efficient if no other cell makes both players better off.

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; check Pareto in BoS -->
```scheme
(define (pareto-dominates? cell1 cell2)
  (and (>= (car cell1) (car cell2))
       (>= (cadr cell1) (cadr cell2))
       (or (> (car cell1) (car cell2))
           (> (cadr cell1) (cadr cell2)))))

(let ((cells (list (list 2 1) (list 0 0) (list 0 0) (list 1 2))))
  (map (lambda (c)
         (list 'cell c 'dominated-by
               (filter (lambda (other) (pareto-dominates? other c)) cells)))
       cells))
```
[VISUAL: shows (0,0) cells are Pareto-dominated by (2,1) or (1,2).]

---

## 7. Summit: Solve a Nim position and simulate a juggling pattern

**Opening: the capstone programs**

We've journeyed from Nim's ancient piles to surreal infinities, from minimax trees to siteswap rhythms. Now we tie it together with two standalone artifacts: (1) a Nim solver that takes arbitrary heaps, computes the Grundy number, finds all winning moves, and visualizes the game tree; (2) a siteswap validator-and-simulator that takes a pattern, checks it, counts the balls, and animates the throw sequence.

---

### 7a. Summit artifact I: Complete Nim solver and game tree

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; full Nim analysis + tree -->
```scheme
;; --- Nim Solver: given heaps, analyze and solve ---

(define (nim-analysis heaps)
  (let* ((nim-sum (game/nim-sum heaps))
         (outcome (game/nim-outcome heaps))
         (is-losing (= nim-sum 0))
         (winning-moves (if is-losing
                            '()
                            (let loop ((i 0) (acc '()))
                              (if (>= i (length heaps))
                                  (reverse acc)
                                  (let* ((pile (list-ref heaps i))
                                         (desired (game/nim-sum (list pile nim-sum))))
                                    (loop (+ i 1)
                                          (if (and (>= desired 0) (< desired pile))
                                              (cons (list 'pile i 'from pile 'to desired 'remove (- pile desired)) acc)
                                              acc))))))))
    (list 'heaps heaps
          'nim-sum nim-sum
          'outcome outcome
          'status (if is-losing 'losing-position 'winning-position)
          'winning-moves winning-moves)))

(define example-heaps (list 3 5 7))
(nim-analysis example-heaps)
```
[VISUAL: text output showing full analysis: heaps, nim-sum, outcome, whether position is winning/losing, and list of all winning moves.]

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; build Nim game tree to depth 3 -->
```scheme
;; --- Nim Game Tree: recursive tree showing all positions ---

(define (nim-game-tree heaps depth)
  (if (<= depth 0)
      (list 'heaps heaps 'nim-sum (game/nim-sum heaps) 'outcome (game/nim-outcome heaps) 'terminal #t)
      (let* ((nim-sum (game/nim-sum heaps))
             (outcome (game/nim-outcome heaps))
             (moves (let loop ((i 0) (acc '()))
                      (if (>= i (length heaps))
                          (reverse acc)
                          (let* ((pile (list-ref heaps i))
                                 (takes (comb/range 1 (+ pile 1))))
                            (loop (+ i 1)
                                  (append acc (map (lambda (t)
                                                     (let ((new-heaps (map (lambda (j h)
                                                                             (if (= j i) (- h t) h))
                                                                           (comb/range 0 (length heaps))
                                                                           heaps)))
                                                       (list 'pile i 'take t 'result new-heaps)))
                                                   takes)))))))
             (children (map (lambda (move)
                              (nim-game-tree (cadr (assoc 'result move)) (- depth 1)))
                            moves)))
        (list 'heaps heaps 'nim-sum nim-sum 'outcome outcome 'depth depth 'children children))))

(nim-game-tree (list 2 3) 2)
```
[VISUAL: nested tree structure showing position (2,3), its nim-sum and outcome, and all descendant positions down to depth 2, with their nim-sums and outcomes. Fully navigable game tree.]

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; print winning path from a winning position -->
```scheme
;; --- Find and display the winning path ---

(define (winning-path heaps)
  (let ((nim-sum (game/nim-sum heaps)))
    (if (= nim-sum 0)
        (list 'position-is-losing)
        (let loop ((i 0))
          (if (>= i (length heaps))
              '(error-no-move)
              (let* ((pile (list-ref heaps i))
                     (desired (game/nim-sum (list pile nim-sum))))
                (if (and (>= desired 0) (< desired pile))
                    (let* ((move (list 'pile i 'remove (- pile desired)))
                           (new-heaps (map (lambda (j h) (if (= j i) desired h))
                                           (comb/range 0 (length heaps))
                                           heaps))
                           (new-nim (game/nim-sum new-heaps)))
                      (list 'from heaps 'move move 'to new-heaps 'new-nim-sum new-nim 'outcome 'opponent-loses))
                    (loop (+ i 1)))))))))

(winning-path (list 3 5 7))
```
[VISUAL: `(from (3 5 7) move (pile 0 remove 1) to (2 5 7) new-nim-sum 0 outcome 'opponent-loses)` — explicit winning move and resulting position.]

<!-- BUILD: run in interpreter; simulate a full game with optimal play -->
```scheme
;; --- Simulate Nim game: two players, both optimal ---

(define (play-nim heaps)
  (let loop ((h heaps) (turn 0) (history '()))
    (let ((nim-sum (game/nim-sum h)))
      (
")
